        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The primary purpose of this Science Goal is detecting the [CII]157 emission 
(rest-frame wavelength and frequency: 157.741 micron and 1900.537 GHz) in a 
galaxy COSMOS XID147 at z_opt = 2.941. For this redshift, the observed-frame 
wavelength and frequency are 621.657 micron and 482.247 GHz, respectively. This 
corresponds to a frequency where the atmospheric transmission is relatively good 
in the Band 8. Since the expected velocity width of the [CII]157 emission is 
broad (~1500 km/s), we observe the [CII]157 emission line by using 2 basebands 
(Baseband-1 and Baseband-2) with the lowest resolution (widest coverage; 1875 
MHz) mode. This setup results in the frequency coverage from 480.51 GHz to 
483.98 GHz (that corresponds to the velocity width of ~2200 km/s). The remaining 
2 basebands are used to detect the continuum emission. Since a wide-coverage 
setting is preferred for detecting the continuum emission, we select the widest 
coverage mode also for these 2 basebands. We set the frequency separation 
between Baseband-3 and Baseband-4 to be 1.6 GHz, for covering the continuum 
emission continuously without a gap between 2 basebands. For reducing the data 
rate of this science goal, we adopt 8 channel binning in Baseband-1 and 
Baseband-2 (for [CII]157) and 16 channel binning for the remaining 2 basebands 
(for continuum). This results in the data rate of 2.0 MB/sec, that is below the 
"expected average data rate" (6 MB/sec). Note that this velocity binning does 
not affect our scientific analysis at all, because the resulting velocity 
resolution in Baseband-1 and Baseband-2 (~2.4 km/s, after the 8 channel binning) 
is much finer than any velocity structures expected for sub-millimeter spectra 
of galaxies.

Thanks to the deep multi-wavelength observations, the SED of this source is well 
determined through the Subaru, Spitzer, and Herschel data. The FIR luminosity 
inferred from the SED fitting is 3 x 10^46 erg/s. We assume the luminosity ratio 
of log (L_[CII]/L_FIR) = -3.5 rather conservatively as a high-redshift source 
(note that this luminosity ratio is larger for higher redshift galaxies), based 
on some recent reports (e.g., Maiolino et al. 2009, A&amp;A, 500, L1; Swinbank 
et al. 2012, MN, 427, 1066). Then we obtain the expected [CII] luminosity of 
L_[CII] = 1 x 10^43 erg/s, which results in F_[CII] = 1.3 x 10^-16 erg/s/cm^2 
that corresponds to 5.4 mJy by assuming the velocity width of 1500 km/s. In 
order to detect this [CII]157 emission with S/N = 10, the required sensitivity 
is 0.54 mJy (rms). By adopting 150 km/s velocity width for the time estimate (to 
see possible velocity structure in the ~1500 km/s width emission line), the 
required observing time is 1.20 hours (on-source), that corresponds to 2.70 
hours including calibrations and overheads. 

For this Science Goal, we do not need to resolve the internal structure for each 
component. Thus the required angular resolution is specified to be 1.0 arcsec. 
Therefore we do not use the ACA. No scheduling time constraints for this Science 
Goal.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
